          <p>The Sun is a G-type main-sequence star (G2V) that formed 4.6 billion years ago and contains 99.86% of the mass in our Solar System. It converts 620 million metric tons of hydrogen into helium every second through nuclear fusion, generating all the energy that sustains life on Earth from 150 million kilometers away.</p>
